div.p:
Embdes 644 of course raises an important question of principle, which is not limited in its application to Colombia, and that is whether the loans we make or finance will have as a result the encouragement of liberal trade practices (which in turn are directly related to the progress of democracy in the Embassy’s opinion), or whether they will have the opposite result. It also is based on following premise:
(1) That prudent government bankers like prudent private bankers in scrutinizing loan applications have not only the right but the obligation to inquire into the details of the applicant’s business; (2) that Colombia like other subscribers to the International Bank is committed in various instruments to pursue liberal trade policies;
(3) the pursuit of liberal trade policies is in the interest of Colombia’s credit; and (4) Exim and World Bank credits are not intended to substitute for private investment.
